TY  - JOUR
AU  - Karakas¸, Oğuzhan
AU  - Mohseni, Mahdi
T1  - Staggered Boards and the Value of Voting Rights
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfab004
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 10
IS  - 3
SP  - 513
EP  - 550
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - This paper examines the impact of staggered boards on the value of voting rights (i.e., the voting premium) estimated using option prices. We find companies with staggered boards have a higher voting premium. Exploiting plausibly exogenous court rulings, we confirm that weakening the effectiveness of staggered boards decreases the voting premium. Given that the voting premium reflects private benefits consumption and associated managerial inefficiencies, our findings are consistent with the entrenchment view of staggered boards. Analyzing the cross-sectional heterogeneity in our sample, we find the entrenchment effect of staggered boards to be particularly pronounced for firms in noncompetitive industries and for mature firms. (JEL G13, G30, G34, K22)
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfab004
ER  - 



